        -:  213:/** \class Ref
        -:  214:  * \ingroup Core_Module
        -:  215:  *
        -:  216:  * \brief A matrix or vector expression mapping an existing expression
        -:  217:  *
        -:  218:  * \tparam PlainObjectType the equivalent matrix type of the mapped data
        -:  219:  * \tparam Options specifies the pointer alignment in bytes. It can be: \c #Aligned128, , \c #Aligned64, \c #Aligned32, \c #Aligned16, \c #Aligned8 or \c #Unaligned.
        -:  220:  *                 The default is \c #Unaligned.
        -:  221:  * \tparam StrideType optionally specifies strides. By default, Ref implies a contiguous storage along the inner dimension (inner stride==1),
        -:  222:  *                   but accepts a variable outer stride (leading dimension).
        -:  223:  *                   This can be overridden by specifying strides.
        -:  224:  *                   The type passed here must be a specialization of the Stride template, see examples below.
        -:  225:  *
        -:  226:  * This class provides a way to write non-template functions taking Eigen objects as parameters while limiting the number of copies.
        -:  227:  * A Ref<> object can represent either a const expression or a l-value:
        -:  228:  * \code
        -:  229:  * // in-out argument:
        -:  230:  * void foo1(Ref<VectorXf> x);
        -:  231:  *
        -:  232:  * // read-only const argument:
        -:  233:  * void foo2(const Ref<const VectorXf>& x);
        -:  234:  * \endcode
        -:  235:  *
        -:  236:  * In the in-out case, the input argument must satisfy the constraints of the actual Ref<> type, otherwise a compilation issue will be triggered.
        -:  237:  * By default, a Ref<VectorXf> can reference any dense vector expression of float having a contiguous memory layout.
        -:  238:  * Likewise, a Ref<MatrixXf> can reference any column-major dense matrix expression of float whose column's elements are contiguously stored with
        -:  239:  * the possibility to have a constant space in-between each column, i.e. the inner stride must be equal to 1, but the outer stride (or leading dimension)
        -:  240:  * can be greater than the number of rows.
        -:  241:  *
        -:  242:  * In the const case, if the input expression does not match the above requirement, then it is evaluated into a temporary before being passed to the function.
        -:  243:  * Here are some examples:
        -:  244:  * \code
        -:  245:  * MatrixXf A;
        -:  246:  * VectorXf a;
        -:  247:  * foo1(a.head());             // OK
        -:  248:  * foo1(A.col());              // OK
        -:  249:  * foo1(A.row());              // Compilation error because here innerstride!=1
        -:  250:  * foo2(A.row());              // Compilation error because A.row() is a 1xN object while foo2 is expecting a Nx1 object
        -:  251:  * foo2(A.row().transpose());  // The row is copied into a contiguous temporary
        -:  252:  * foo2(2*a);                  // The expression is evaluated into a temporary
        -:  253:  * foo2(A.col().segment(2,4)); // No temporary
        -:  254:  * \endcode
        -:  255:  *
        -:  256:  * The range of inputs that can be referenced without temporary can be enlarged using the last two template parameters.
        -:  257:  * Here is an example accepting an innerstride!=1:
        -:  258:  * \code
        -:  259:  * // in-out argument:
        -:  260:  * void foo3(Ref<VectorXf,0,InnerStride<> > x);
        -:  261:  * foo3(A.row());              // OK
        -:  262:  * \endcode
        -:  263:  * The downside here is that the function foo3 might be significantly slower than foo1 because it won't be able to exploit vectorization, and will involve more
        -:  264:  * expensive address computations even if the input is contiguously stored in memory. To overcome this issue, one might propose to overload internally calling a
        -:  265:  * template function, e.g.:
        -:  266:  * \code
        -:  267:  * // in the .h:
        -:  268:  * void foo(const Ref<MatrixXf>& A);
        -:  269:  * void foo(const Ref<MatrixXf,0,Stride<> >& A);
        -:  270:  *
        -:  271:  * // in the .cpp:
        -:  272:  * template<typename TypeOfA> void foo_impl(const TypeOfA& A) {
        -:  273:  *     ... // crazy code goes here
        -:  274:  * }
        -:  275:  * void foo(const Ref<MatrixXf>& A) { foo_impl(A); }
        -:  276:  * void foo(const Ref<MatrixXf,0,Stride<> >& A) { foo_impl(A); }
        -:  277:  * \endcode
        -:  278:  *
        -:  279:  * See also the following stackoverflow questions for further references:
        -:  280:  *  - <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/21132538/correct-usage-of-the-eigenref-class">Correct usage of the Eigen::Ref<> class</a>
        -:  281:  *
        -:  282:  * \sa PlainObjectBase::Map(), \ref TopicStorageOrders
        -:  283:  */
